[{"id":27159,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b12d7da-dda6-4e69-8c19-a1a8d99d026d-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 121px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0187a603-2ba3-48f7-b61f-c555d08c7068-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 130px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7f3f3b26-3dc8-4ec4-8c6b-6c1c47da8b00-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 119px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5ffcaff7-dc13-451b-adde-71550fc7fcc3-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 121px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f0c40f17-d116-4b8b-9947-6c9fb95c1dfb-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 125px;\" /><br /><br />NaBH<sub>4</sub>&nbsp; reduce the&nbsp;carbonyl into alcohol</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27055,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8Ohnwu9rlWdne9bK3r9kCfS_uORX8JSCc0c1s46Brp0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/awRCg_zRQ5VbaNTLvB44cMjEdK9znJQBwJWljoz-mCg.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/YLceETangUWsFWW4yRBDUx_R4rpt39W1d7G6aJhE2v8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/LmowPiFPWmQfs4QZnBRYovrPwYghEQ1DL8wS6H74Dqc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hc8GAVD2pzCbwLrG38aG4lFZ9MHk7YGdk5zCUpwO08c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27093,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>This reaction is an example of intra molecular Claisen condensation reaction.&nbsp;The mechanism of the Claisen condensation reaction proceeds with the removal of an alpha proton through the action of a strong base to result in the formation of an enolate ion.&nbsp;</p><p>This results the formation products as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/03e6b3b6-d2c4-4655-8970-9e3e71778acb-image.png\" style=\"width: 324px; height: 150px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27136,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>≈</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&lt;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>d</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>P</mi><msub><mrow><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>P</mi><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>O</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mn>4</mn><msup><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><msup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi><mi>N</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> <math><mi>N</mi><msup><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> <math><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><msup><mrow><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi>O</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> <math><mi>N</mi><msup><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>W</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> <math><msubsup><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mtext> </mtext><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mtext> </mtext><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><msubsup><mrow><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi></mi><mtext> </mtext><mn>1</mn></mrow></msubsup></math> So, unpaired electron is <math><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>8</mn></msqrt><mi></mi><mi>B</mi><mi>M</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27090,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0dc27cfe-8f6c-4279-b31c-2f399088fd16-image.png\" style=\"width: 193px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c600f29e-0a40-4510-96e0-ff39b73ac9f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/74497835-2f6e-4d0a-a7c1-9ea1d9ae8beb-image.png\" style=\"width: 199px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4fe711e8-058f-4027-933b-54bd55787528-image.png\" style=\"width: 211px; height: 100px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>This reaction is an example of aldol reaction. The product formation is shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/205d5ee2-5af2-4eba-a9fb-237dd481c2c9-cc784751-a844-4dca-8344-29b88e264ab9-image.png\" style=\"width: 612px; height: 329px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27160,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/087ff6e4-1297-47d9-a6f1-b136d4fad7f2-image.png\" style=\"width: 190px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8406694b-7e6d-43e8-9fbe-49ae188e4596-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 115px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/553bb498-867d-4c74-8621-aefaf74310a0-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 124px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a6bce176-73a9-421d-8da3-e2188af5116a-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 118px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d05b9142-ea4d-47cb-b28a-0fb676073900-3-5-2022tdo.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 307px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27057,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><b>DIBAL</b>-<b>H</b><b> </b>i.e., Di isobutyl aluminium hydride causes partial reduction of cyanide group along with the ester group and further hydrolysis forms corresponding aldehyde as the product. The reaction is as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><mtext> DIBAL- </mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></math></p><p>The Clemmensen reduction is a reaction that is used to reduce aldehydes or ketones to alkanes using hydrochloric acid and zinc amalgam.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>COC</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&amp;</mo><mtext> conc. </mtext><mi>HCl</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p><p>A Grignard reagent is an organomagnesium compound which can be described by the <em>chemical formula ‘R-Mg-X’</em><em> </em>. Here aldehyde will react with Grignard's reagent to give alcohol.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi><munderover><mo>→</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></mrow></munderover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></mrow></mover><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p><p>In this reaction, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> is used as a reducing agent, to get <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>COOC</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math> as a product.</p><p>Hence option B is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (01 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27094,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"In an aldol condensation, an enolate ion reacts with a carbonyl compound in the presence of acid/base catalyst to form a &beta;-hydroxy aldehyde or &beta;-hydroxy ketone, followed by dehydration to give a conjugated enone. It is a useful carbon-carbon bond-forming reaction.<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b59c8e8e-e6b3-4da4-aee5-6f80f033991a-9711756_2.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 185px;\" /></p><p>As there are 2 pi bonds in the major product(P), the number of pi electrons will be equal to 4.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27016,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["2-Methylpent-4-en-3-one","4-Methylpent-3-en-2-one","4-Methylpent-1-ene","2-Methylpent-3-one"],"answer":1,"solution":"Hydrolysis of prop-1-yne in the presence of $HgSO_4$ and dilute $H_2SO_4$ yields acetone.<br><br>$CH_3-C \\equiv CH + H_2O \\xrightarrow{Hg^{2+}, H^+} CH_3-CO-CH_3$<br><br>Thus, $x$ is acetone.<br><br>Reaction of ethane nitrile ($CH_3CN$) with methyl magnesium bromide ($CH_3MgBr$) followed by hydrolysis also yields acetone.<br><br>$CH_3-C \\equiv N + CH_3MgBr \\rightarrow CH_3-C(CH_3)=NMgBr \\xrightarrow{H_3O^+} CH_3-CO-CH_3$<br><br>Thus, $y$ is acetone.<br><br>Reaction of $x$ and $y$ (both acetone) in the presence of $Ba(OH)_2$ followed by heating results in an aldol condensation.<br><br>$2 CH_3-CO-CH_3 \\xrightarrow{Ba(OH)_2} CH_3-C(OH)(CH_3)-CH_2-CO-CH_3$<br><br>Heating causes dehydration to form an unsaturated ketone.<br><br>$CH_3-C(OH)(CH_3)-CH_2-CO-CH_3 \\xrightarrow{\\Delta} CH_3-C(CH_3)=CH-CO-CH_3$<br><br>Numbering the principal carbon chain to give the lowest locant to the ketone group, the IUPAC name of the product is 4-methylpent-3-en-2-one.<br><br>Answer: 4-Methylpent-3-en-2-one","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27066,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8c3ba512-92ea-48b2-962a-b4aa2447b91a.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 156px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/19e7f829-8200-484f-bbcd-454c9f67ef00.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 124px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/89ba1116-2c0b-4b32-abd5-ae6025645fff.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 117px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28d07189-747b-469b-8309-a4ef5d6e4b4d.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 83px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Intramolecular Aldol condensations happen when a single molecule contains two&nbsp;aldehyde/ketone groups. When the alpha carbon of one group attacks the other, the molecule attacks itself forming a ring structure. The reaction is shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/339f8e83-8405-4d6a-a25c-16bfc14450dc.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 260px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27058,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Stephen reaction","Etard reaction","Gatterman-koch reaction","Rosenmund reduction"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Gattermann – Koch reaction is used for the industrial production of benzaldehyde. </p><p>In Gattermann – Koch reaction, benzene is treated with carbon monoxide in the acidic medium in presence of anhydrous aluminium chloride to give benzaldehyde. In this reaction, anhydrous aluminium chloride works as a catalyst. It is an electrophilic substitution reaction.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa7eeb78-cb04-4862-a172-6589570c1d9e.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 183px;\"/></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27101,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pd</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Na</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Sodium reacts with Hydrogen to form sodium hydride.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaH</mi></math></p><p>So&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Na</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;cannot be used for reduction of functional groups.</p><p>All other reagents are used as reducing agent.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27177,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Acetone","Formaldehyde","Benzophenone","None of these"],"answer":1,"solution":"Formaldehyde and Acetaldehyde can be oxidized by tollen's reagent to give silver mirror.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":27126,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["(I)-(Q), (II)-(R) and (III)-(P)","(I)-(P), (II)-(Q) and (III)-(R)","(I)-(R), (II)-(P) and (III)-(Q)","(I)-(R), (II)-(Q) and (III)-(P)"],"answer":2,"solution":"<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/52ab7133-1e59-45aa-bd63-284c92203f92-image.png\" style=\"width: 337px; height: 179px;\" /></td>\t\t\t<td>Gatterman-Koach reaction</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/610ade81-2f08-4913-9924-931e06413d64-image.png\" style=\"width: 366px; height: 164px;\" /> Reduction</td>\t\t\t<td>Stephan Reduction</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d6500930-58f2-4728-bf4e-5bd7e33f4c07-image.png\" style=\"width: 333px; height: 172px;\" /></td>\t\t\t<td>Rosenmund Reduction</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27171,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Schiff's reagent","Tollen's reagent","$\\mathrm{I}_2$ /Alkali","Fehling's solution"],"answer":2,"solution":"Only acetaldehyde and methyl ketones give iodoform test.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27127,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/819b4a33-f154-44b1-858b-323823eda815-image.png\" style=\"width: 232px; height: 104px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3d912ee7-88e2-44b3-b374-862ff2903fd8-c27b5746-baa9-48a7-ab84-6e8eec54581b-image(1).png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 95px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0937df9d-50aa-4476-b267-856e9b7feed5-image.png\" style=\"width: 197px; height: 103px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ac20b7b-4227-4df7-9c52-a8eb112450bc-image.png\" style=\"width: 226px; height: 108px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cfef3717-80c7-47b0-911b-217b3ac0933f-image.png\" style=\"width: 347px; height: 62px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/acd2601a-c0c2-454d-aebf-f15094f10066-image.png\" style=\"width: 475px; height: 417px;\" />Alcohol upon reaction with protic acids tends to lose a molecule of water to form alkenes. These reactions are known as dehydrogenation or dehydration of alcohols. It is an example of an elimination reaction.The order of the ease of dehydration of alcohols is: tertiary &gt; secondary &gt; primary.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27122,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Red&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8861;</mo></mover><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ni</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the given reaction, only the carbonyl group has been reduced while the carbon- carbon double bonds are unaltered.</p><p>This is possible with the help of Wolf Kishner Reduction whose reagent set is given in Opiton (C).</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f6045544-a78e-4433-8fe1-cb2d0e6f4657-YUII.png\" style=\"width: 301px; height: 128px;\" /></p><p>To reduce the carbonyl groups into alkane wolf -&nbsp;kischner reduction is used, without affecting the double bond.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27116,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64004576-3c00-4779-b3b1-22d30ec64191-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f7683456-764d-44bb-a1c0-d66df6b6cc44-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/357d5893-ca55-4435-b485-9f943c51cc29-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2407a54b-185a-4f58-8449-45960750c91d-image.png\" style=\"width: 118px; height: 116px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9a3714b-425f-4e5d-9d8d-a0bde47471db-image.png\" style=\"width: 383px; height: 220px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27037,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m4jCqT73HEzALe4jvqnmtTgyH2nZpXsL5PAg5YaoWOk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/D9Dqp5l-xK0uqZfgHNUgUmSkIQ2lMMcT_uob9lKbXN4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RMgJZfz2GzMWpW7Enw68FGi3zoKDfzi94qZ-q7KQkrQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zWncLLF9wx5RjZSE4QrmvIpbEWtocAM8G1Bdprx3264.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n or<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0uNx_oyH6zbtyWb5MVb9xCe3WjZvbLvqbFfNDO6j8yM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27095,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dacfb354-d5fd-4c04-98f7-f90820f88c93-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 140px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bf4940b9-5cd3-478f-91c8-56f017290290-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 89px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/125f0614-4ee7-48ae-ba9e-00b336f9238e-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 167px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79f70513-9fb9-44ba-895f-f93aa2e219e4-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 135px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In the first step formaldehyde undergoes cross aldol reaction with isobutyraldehyde&nbsp;to form&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong>(</strong><strong>A)</strong>and then the product(A)&nbsp;forms cyanohydrin&nbsp;(B)with KCN, which on hydrolysis forms a compound containing&nbsp;carboxylic acid group and finally this molecule undergoes intramolecular esterification to form (C) a stable compound.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0879d387-d640-4ef6-8e79-7bd40ce84413-image.png\" style=\"width: 560px; height: 368px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27053,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/A1CCzv6CJZ8PUNZ3KRyfZcLtllxYtLDbzcq4mUVCr78.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uFNlBLd6cVWWvRf5QNJ17AyVZF4JNP2nWKbRtdxXoHE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/edBKVVxPp3EwNurAkWJO4fUUBK3JHs6bVimIZ5SSfx8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/G4o8JLy24Mdjycdsn_OcBMD1bSEaTULMGutjXNcGm5k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d4XjQlXPsjhWaoZ8VpF8_wX-JGedPoRCjHXk5XaJt3Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27034,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["But-2-yne","Butan-2-ol","Butan-2-one","Butan-1-al"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KF9fPf4ub9hv_CmI5JFDS_ra4R-RuXXKWtDJWuejftk.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27029,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4TryUlaY9zzZ8kYzfMTLFwWAIheQ5K5_RrlTWu9YUY0.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ov8-kZcA_ilPZJHqmppdExBKSALNY_mGTpLgqd80UlA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/waN4peH_CoSOsF3wY58ZsG_7IgX4qRAvkSDaaEH40Qs.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/n_az6Jl0JoPkx5rvUhffoXRIxQ0kNWcFlPN_sJtflY8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rdQBB7aZCMbqnQCkqtKFlhcFR2wNnmbOgBD-rCm1YMM.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27162,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/750c7422-0e05-442b-abbb-996ce1c48f64-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 130px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81a60774-a5d3-4cce-81bb-7b4d057bbcfb-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 98px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed6c9975-c407-47f0-a17d-94a5a0e2a378-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 96px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8df0ef4-f2a3-4f85-a1f8-7ee297f70c49-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 129px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> (diisobutyl aluminium hydride) reduces carboxylic acid and ester to aldehydes.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27133,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c68b86e9-d82e-495c-8672-1501591becd2-image.png\" style=\"width: 68px; height: 65px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbed7049-0554-4d1f-b314-686a9aa7e797-image.png\" style=\"width: 66px; height: 85px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a22d3132-d985-40ea-8598-6f5ccb781aaa-image.png\" style=\"width: 79px; height: 89px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/572536e9-8260-407f-9d99-48c7e5562af6-image.png\" style=\"width: 73px; height: 102px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The above reaction sequence is given below. In the first step, halogenation reaction is occurred then elimination reaction gives cyclohexene and reductive ozonolysis gives the dialdehyde and then aldol condensation takes place and final desired product is formed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc2bd8e5-de0b-42a3-a770-183d5d3d648c-image.png\" style=\"width: 723px; height: 112px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27036,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A, B and D Only","$C$ and E Only","A, C and E Only","B, C and D Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ltnbapzAFQG1bIvNnPBArPUUz_2KpaDUVp1mLV85o8Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27070,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Acid-base reactions are faster than nucleophilic addition reaction. So, in the first step acid-base reaction takes place between alcoholic functional group and Grignard reagent. Now, the second mole of Grignard reagent to react with aldehyde functional group. Hence, at the end of the reaction a diol is produced on acidification.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/67f1d4b9-c85e-4a6e-817a-7bf45cecac15-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 110px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27161,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The correct order of reagents for the following reaction is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><msup><mo>]</mo><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>&nbsp;&amp; the reaction as well as mechanism is as follows with the correct order of reagents.</p><p>The reaction involves&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SN</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;mechanism at second step which on further reaction with excess&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>MgBr</mi></math>&nbsp;to give the final product.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e18fe0e9-d54d-4d5d-94af-83e2cfcfaa19-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 400px;\" /><br /><br />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27064,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In Fehling’s solution, the reaction between copper(II) ions and aliphatic aldehyde is represented as;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>RCHO</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>→</mo><msup><mi>RCOO</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Cu</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>Hence ,Acetaldehyde <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo></math> Methanal <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>HCHO</mi></mfenced></math>, and cyclohexane carbaldehyde </p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0e701c9d-3a59-4512-8854-e1180091b645.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 130px;\"/></p><p>compounds  gives positive Fehling's test.</p><p>Hence, the answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27098,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> /acetic acid,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> /acetic anhydride,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Anhyd</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Toluene is oxidised to benzaldehyde in presence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> /acetic anhydride,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p><p>Toluene is converted to&nbsp;benzylidene diacetate&nbsp;and&nbsp;hydrolysis reaction of benzylidene diacetate&nbsp;gives benzaldehyde.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9edbce60-686a-4097-85d4-4bea5da15ff4-image.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 175px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null}]